    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Defending Cochlear Implants</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arlene Romonoff letter on Aug 22 article on cochlear implants</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a cochlear implant user, I found the news that cochlear implants had to be proven ''cost effective'' to insurance companies a sad commentary on health care in our country (''Aid for Deaf as Possible Cost-Saver, Too,'' Aug. 22).</p>
        <p>Hearing loss is the most misunderstood and invisible of disabilities. It affects virtually every aspect of daily living, not just education or work productivity. Cochlear implants are modern-day miracles, allowing the deaf to hear and speak.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a cochlear implant user, I found the news that cochlear implants had to be proven ''cost effective'' to insurance companies a sad commentary on health care in our country (''Aid for Deaf as Possible Cost-Saver, Too,'' Aug. 22).</p>
        <p>Hearing loss is the most misunderstood and invisible of disabilities. It affects virtually every aspect of daily living, not just education or work productivity. Cochlear implants are modern-day miracles, allowing the deaf to hear and speak.</p>
        <p>I suggest that insurance company executives try living without sound for a week and put a price on this miracle. They'll find that at today's rates, they are getting a bargain.</p>
        <p>ARLENE ROMOFF  Ridgewood, N.J.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
